{"@context":"http://iiif.io/api/presentation/3/context.json","id":"https://digbmc.github.io/pta-manifests/phan/phan-02950/manifest.json","type":"Manifest","label":{"none":["PHAN-02950"]},"metadata":[{"label":{"none":["Timestamp"]},"value":{"none":["0:29:50"]}},{"label":{"none":["Film"]},"value":{"none":["Phantom Thread"]}},{"label":{"none":["Creator"]},"value":{"none":["Paul Thomas Anderson"]}},{"label":{"none":["Distance"]},"value":{"none":["medium shot"]}},{"label":{"none":["Angle"]},"value":{"none":["low"]}},{"label":{"none":["Location"]},"value":{"none":["interior"]}},{"label":{"none":["Movement"]},"value":{"none":["mobile, handheld"]}},{"label":{"none":["Composition"]},"value":{"none":["two shot"]}}],"summary":{"none":["A man speaks to a woman as she looks visibly uncomfortable."]},"thumbnail":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-02950/tiles/full/300,169/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":169,"width":300}],"homepage":[{"id":"PHAN-02950","type":"Text","format":"text/html","label":{"none":["Object homepage"]}}],"items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-02950/canvas/1","type":"Canvas","height":1080,"width":1920,"label":{"none":["PHAN-02950"]},"thumbnail":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-02950/tiles/full/300,169/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":169,"width":300}],"items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-02950/canvas/1/annopage-1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-02950/canvas/1/annopage-1/anno-1","type":"Annotation","motivation":"painting","target":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-02950/canvas/1","body":{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-02950/tiles/full/1920,1080/0/default.jpg","type":"Image","format":"image/jpeg","height":1080,"width":1920,"service":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-02950/tiles","type":"ImageService3","profile":"http://iiif.io/api/image/3/level0.json"}]}}]}],"annotations":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-02950/canvas/1/page/p1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-02950/canvas/1/4f6a257b-cd2f-4a27-98e1-5f188e85784b","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2026-06-29T20:31:33.324Z","creator":"g","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>Reynolds claims that it’s his “job” to give Alma breasts if he “choose[s] to.” He views his muse as material that he can craft and shape according to his vision to bring to life what he views as an ideal figure. This exchange recalls a passage from Mary Blume’s biography of Spanish designer Cristóbal Balenciaga: “One Sunday in Spain, Balenciaga took [his mentee and French designer Hubert de] Givenchy to his empty atelier. ‘There were all those dummies of Spanish woman who, like anyone at a certain moment in life, Spanish or not, had bent backs and sagging bosoms. Esparza was there and we passed the pins—they had to be passed in a certain way and we couldn’t pass them fast enough—and we could see the woman starting to straighten up. It was wonderful to see little by little, and just with pins, the body rebalance itself. It was plastic surgery to the highest degree” (Blume, <em>The Master of Us All</em>, 139).&nbsp; For these mid-century fashion designers, their work was not only a matter of making clothing for the wealthy but an act of creation that transformed bodies themselves.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>"}],"target":{"type":"SpecificResource","source":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-02950/canvas/1","selector":{"type":"FragmentSelector","conformsTo":"http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/","value":"xywh=pixel:559.4616419919246,91.00942126514141,496.150740242261,421.2113055181695"}}}]}]}]}